headline: Apulia
content: A rebellion breaks out against William II of Sicily, and the Byzantine Empire, encouraged by Pope Hadrian, invades Apulia.   William II crushes the rebellion, defeats the Byzantine armies at Brindisi, and humbles the Pope at Benevento.

headline: Antioch
content: May 18 - The Principality of Antioch, a crusader state, falls to the Mamluk Sultan Baibars in the Battle of Antioch; Baibars' destruction of the city of Antioch is so great as to permanently negate the city's importance.

headline: Antioch
content: The Eastern Orthodox Patriarchy of Antioch returns to Antioch after a 171-year exile, during which it had been replaced by the Latin Patriarch of Antioch.

headline: Antioch
content: Plotinus, Greek philosopher, escapes the bloodshed that accompanies the murder of Gordianus III and makes his way to Antioch. Back to Rome he founds his Neoplatonist school and attracts students like Porphyry, Castricius Firmus and Eustochius of Alexandria.

headline: Antioch
content: March 5?Emperor Julian moves from Antioch with an army of 90,000 against the Sassanid Empire.

headline: Antioch
content: Sayf al-Daula raids into the Byzantine theme of Lykandos but is defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and the raiding as far south as Antioch. Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis for Byzantium.Stanford, CA  isbn = 978-0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page = 489}}<

headline: Antioch
content: October 22?The temple of Apollo at Daphne, outside Antioch, is destroyed in a mysterious fire.

headline: Antioch
content: 28 October?Byzantine general Michael Bourtzes seizes part of Antioch's fortifications. The capture of the city from the Arabs is completed three days later, when reinforcements under Peter Phokas arrive.

headline: Antioch
content: The Sassanid king, Shapur I, orders an invasion of the Roman East with the intent of finally capturing the jewel of Syria, Antioch (251?254).

headline: Antioch
content: Battle of Issus: Emperor Septimius Severus marches with his army (12 legions) to Cilicia and defeats Pescennius Niger, governor of Syria. He retreats to Antioch and  is executed by Severus' troops.

headline: Antioch
content: The disciples of Jesus form communities after the Diaspora, especially in Damascus and Antioch.  For the first time they are called Christians.

headline: Antioch
content: Alexander Severus assembled the Roman army and establish his headquarters at Antioch. He makes an attempt for diplomatic solutions, but the Persians decline and choose for war.

headline: Antioch
content: Natural disaster: An earthquake strikes Antioch, killing thousands, and causing a fire that destroys the Great Church built by Constantine I.

headline: Antioch
content: August 14 - Battle of Hab: Baldwin II of Jerusalem's Crusaders defeat Ilghazi's army, saving Antioch.

headline: Antioch
content: Late May (probably between the 20th and the 29th)?An earthquake kills approximately 250,000 in Syria and Antioch.

headline: Antioch
content: Autumn?winter?The Byzantine general Heraclius, brother of Tiberius III, launches a campaign into Syria, defeats an army from Antioch and raids as far as Samosata.Stanford, CA  isbn = 0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page=339}}<

headline: Antarctica
content: At 6:50 PM, a volcano erupts on Deception Island in Antarctica.

headline: Antarctica
content: January 19 - Captain Charles Wilkes circumnavigates Antarctica, claiming what becomes known as Wilkes Land for the United States.

headline: Antarctica
content: November 28 - Air New Zealand Flight 901: an Air New Zealand DC-10 crashes into Mount Erebus (in Antarctica) on a sightseeing trip, killing all 257 people on board.

headline: Antarctica
content: December 1 - Cold War - Antarctic Treaty: 12 countries, including the United States and the Soviet Union, sign a landmark treaty, which sets aside Antarctica as a scientific preserve and bans military activity on that continent (the first arms control agreement established during the Cold War).

headline: Antarctica
content: January 20 - Dumont D'Urville discovers Adelie Land, Antarctica.

headline: Antarctica
content: July 21 - The lowest temperature on earth is recorded in Vostok Station, Antarctica with ?89.2 ﾰC (?128.6 ﾰF).

headline: Antananarivo
content: March 17 - The President of Madagascar, Marc Ravalomanana, is overthrown in a ''coup d'etat'', following a month of rallies in Antananarivo. The military appoints opposition leader Andry Rajoelina as the new president.BBC Newsaccessdate= 17 March 2009}}<

headline: Annapurna
content: June 3 - Annapurna I, 10th highest mountain in the world, is first ascended.

headline: Ankara
content: November 15 - Middle East Technical University is founded in Ankara, Turkey.

headline: Ankara
content: April 26 - The government of Turkey declares a state of siege in 11 provinces, Ankara included, due to violent demonstrations.

headline: Ankara
content: Raymond IV of Toulouse, count of Tripoli, takes Ankara from the Seljuk Turks.

headline: Ankara
content: February 23 ? Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah ecalan is charged with treason in Ankara, Turkey.

headline: Anjouan
content: August 9 ? In the Comoros, the Military Committee of Major Mohamad Bacar seizes power in the island of Anjouan, which had declared independence. They plan to rejoin the Comoros.

headline: Anjou
content: February 26 - Battle of Benevento: The army of Charles, Count of Anjou, defeats a combined German and Sicilian force led by King Manfred of Sicily.  Manfred is killed in the battle and Pope Clement IV invests Charles as king of Sicily and Naples.

headline: Anjou
content: With the death of Duke Charles IV of Anjou, Anjou reverts to the French crown under Louis XI of France.

headline: Anjou
content: April - Philip of Anjou marries Mary of Naples, daughter of Charles of Valois, duke of Calabria, and Mary of Valois.

headline: Anjou
content: Odo, Count of Paris becomes Count of Anjou on the death of Hugh the Abbot.

headline: Anjou
content: October 20 - Philip of Anjou, Titular Emperor of Constantinople, marries Elisabeth of Slavonia, daughter of Stephen, duke of Transylvania and Slavonia, and Margareta of Bavaria.

headline: Anjou
content: Anjou is conquered by Philip II of France.  Fearing a French invasion of England itself, John of England requires every English male over 12 to enter an association for the general defence of the realm and the preservation of peace.

headline: Anhui
content: Each family holding colonized land in Anhui province has to plant 200 each of mulberry, jujube and persimmon trees

headline: Anhui
content: March 24 - Taiping Rebellion: Suspecting treachery on the part of East King Yang Xiuqing, Shi Dakai garrisons Anhui and begins his march back to the Heavenly Capital, having defeated a strong Xiang Army dettachment.

headline: Anhui
content: March 17 - Taiping Rebellion: A Taiping army of 350,000 invades Anhui.

headline: Angkor
content: Jayavarman IV succeeds Isanavarman II in the Khmer Empire, and moves the capital north from Angkor to Koh Ker.

headline: Anfield
content: March 15 - The Liverpool Football Club is founded by John Houlding, the owner of Anfield. Houlding decides to form his own team after Everton leaves Anfield in an argument over rent.

headline: Andeya
content: January 25 - Norwegian rocket incident: A rocket launched from the space exploration centre at Andeya, Norway is briefly interpreted by the Russians as an incoming attack.

headline: Anderitum
content: A Romano-Celtic{{Citation neededdate=January 2010}} temple-mausoleum complex is constructed in what is now Lullingstone, and also in Anderitum (approximate date).

headline: Anatolia
content: Sayf al-Daula leads 30,000 men in a raid into Byzantine Anatolia. He defeats Bardas Phokas, but is then ambushed on his return and heavily defeated by Leo Phokas.Stanford, CA  isbn = 978-0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  pages = 489}}<

headline: Anatolia
content: October - Mongol commander Baiju (operating under Hulagu Khan's command) leads his forces in a victory over Kay Ka'us II of the Sultanate of Rem, thereby capturing Anatolia.

headline: Anatolia
content: Battle of Akroinon in Anatolia, a significant Byzantine victory over the Umayyads, halts the impetus of Arab attacks into Anatolia.

headline: Anatolia
content: Publius Cornelius Tacitus is Governor of the Roman province of Asia, Anatolia.

headline: Anatolia
content: The Goths, coming from Ukraine, cross the Danube and devastate the Roman Empire up to the border with Anatolia.

headline: Anatolia
content: Osman I, founder of the Ottoman Empire, becomes ''bey'' of the Seget tribe in central Anatolia; in 1299 he will declare independence from the Seljuk Turks, marking the birth of the Ottoman Empire.

headline: Anatolia
content: December 27 - The 1939 Erzincan earthquake in Eastern Anatolia, Turkey, kills 30,000.

headline: Anatolia
content: The Ottomans take Philadelphia, the last Byzantine enclave of any significance in Anatolia.

headline: Anatolia
content: The first civil revolt in Anatolia takes place, led by Alevi preacher Celel.

headline: Anatolia
content: The Seljuk Turks storm Anatolia, taking Caesarea and Ani, marking the beginning of Turkish incursions into Anatolia.

headline: Anapji
content: In Korea, Anapji was constructed by order of King Munmu.

headline: Amstel
content: The tea house Mellow Yellow opens on the Amstel River in Amsterdam, pioneering the legal sale of cannabis in the Netherlands.

headline: Amritsar
content: June 6 - Indian troops storm the Golden Temple at Amritsar, the Sikhs' holiest shrine, killing an estimated 2,000 people.

headline: Amritsar
content: June 5 - The Indian government begins Operation Blue Star, the planned attack on the Golden Temple in Amritsar.

headline: Amorium
content: Byzantine Empire: March?The Umayyads under Maslamah ibn Abd al-Malik capture and sack the Byzantine city of Tyana after a prolonged siege, and following a victory over a Byzantine relief army. Maslamah also leads another expedition in the summer, and defeats a Byzantine force near Amorium.Stanford, CA  isbn = 0-8047-2630-2  url = http://books.google.com/books?id=nYbnr5XVbzUC  page=341}}<

headline: Amorium
content: The Byzantine emperor Theophilos is heavily defeated at the Battle of Anzen by the Abbasids. Caliph al-Mu'tasim then proceeds to capture and raze Amorium, the native city of the Byzantine Empire's reigning Amorian dynasty.

headline: Amman
content: Fighting breaks out between Arab guerillas and government forces in Amman, Jordan.

headline: Amman
content: November 9 ? At least 50 people are killed and more than 120 injured in a series of coordinated suicide bombings in Amman, Jordan (See 2005 Amman bombings).

headline: Americas
content: July 30 - In Jamestown, Virginia, the first representative assembly in the Americas, the House of Burgesses, convenes for the first time.

headline: Americas
content: May 12 - The National University of San Marcos is founded in Lima (Peru), being the first officially established university in the Americas.

headline: Americas
content: April 25 - Martin Waldseemeller publishes his world map, naming the new continent America in honour of Amerigo Vespucci (However, the accuracy of this is still debated).

headline: Americas
content: August 3 - Christopher Columbus sails the ocean blue on his first journey across the Atlantic Ocean to Asia, but he ends up in the Americas

headline: Americas
content: In or about this year, one person returning to Haiti from the Congo is thought to have first brought HIV to the Americas.
